{"title_page": "Mstislav Mstislavich", "text_new": "{{for|Mstislav the Daring of Chernigov|Mstislav of Chernigov}}\n[[File:\u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0430) \u0438 \u0414\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0439.jpg|thumb|Detail from the [[Millennium of Russia]] Monument: Mstislav Mstislavich, left, and Daniel of Galicia, his son-in-law]]\n\n'''Mstislav Mstislavich the Daring''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432 II \u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0423\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439}}, {{lang-uk|\u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430&#769;\u0432 \u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430&#769;\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0423\u0434\u0430&#769;\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0439<ref>The original nickname was The Lucky (or The Fortunate), \"Udatny\", later transformed to \"Udaloy\", i.e. The Bold.</ref>}}) (c. 978 \u2013 1036) [[prince]] of [[Tmutarakan]] and [[Chernigov]]<ref>Profiles of great Russians, army and navy, Sankt Petersburg 2008 (ISBN 978-7580-0019-9), page 10; translation: Mistislav the Bold &nbsp;\nPrince of Tmutarakan and Chernigov.</ref>, was one of the most popular and active princes of [[Kievan Rus']] in the decades preceding the [[Mongol invasion of Russia|Mongol invasion of Rus']].{{Attribution needed|date=September 2013}} He was the maternal grandfather of Prince [[Alexander Nevsky]], [[Prince of Novgorod]], [[Grand Prince of Kiev]] and [[Grand Prince of Vladimir]]. He also was the maternal grandfather of prince [[Lev Danylovich|Leo of Galicia]], who became [[Grand Prince of Kiev]].\n\nHe was the son of [[Mstislav Rostislavich|Mstislav the Brave]] of [[Smolensk]] by a princess of [[Ryazan]]. In 1193 and 1203, his bravery in the [[Kipchaks|Kypchak]] wars brought him fame all over Kievan Rus'. At that time, he married Maria, a daughter of Kypchak [[Khan (title)|Khan]] [[Koten|Kotian]]. In 1209 he was mentioned as a ruler of [[Principality of Toropets|Toropets]]. A year later, he came and took the [[Novgorod]]ian throne, seizing [[Sviatoslav Vsevolodovich of Vladimir|Sviatoslav Vsevolodovich]]'s men (Sviatoslav himself was detained in the archbishop's compound in Novgorod).<ref>Michael C. Paul, \"Was the Prince of Novgorod a 'Third-rate Bureaucrat' after 1136?\" ''Jahrb\u00fccher f\u00fcr Geschichte Osteuropas'' 56, No. 1 (2008): 91.</ref>\n\nOn his way to Novgorod, Mstislav delivered the key town of [[Torzhok]] from a siege laid to it by [[Vsevolod the Big Nest|Vsevolod&nbsp;III]] of [[Vladimir, Russia|Vladimir]]. He led two successful Novgorodian campaigns against the [[Chud]]es in 1212 and 1214. In 1215, he expelled [[Vsevolod IV of Kiev|Vsevolod&nbsp;IV]] from [[Kiev]] and elevated his uncle [[Mstislav III of Kiev|Mstislav Romanovich]] to the throne.<ref>Paul, \"Third-rate Bureaucrat\" 91-92.</ref>\n\nIn 1216, Mstislav mustered a large coalition of princes of Rus' which defeated [[Vladimir-Suzdal]] on the [[Battle of Lipitsa|Lipitsa River]]. After that he installed his ally [[Konstantin of Rostov]] as [[Grand Prince of Vladimir]] and married his own daughter to [[Yaroslav II of Russia|Yaroslav of Vladimir]], who had fortified himself in Torzhok. In the meantime, his other enemies had him deposed in Novgorod, and Mstislav had to abandon Northern Rus for [[Halych]]. In 1219, he concluded peace with his chief rival, [[Danylo of Halych]], who thereupon married Mstislav's daughter Anna.{{Citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nIn 1223, Mstislav joined a coalition of perhaps 18 princes, which, along with [[Cuman]] (Polovtsian) allies, pursued the [[Mongols]] from the Dnieper River for nine days and joined battle with them at [[Battle of the Kalka River|Kalka River]].  While three princes were captured and later killed at the battle site, and six more were killed in headlong pursuit back to the Dnieper River, Mstislav is the only prince specifically named among the nine or so who escaped.  He managed to escape by cutting loose the boats on the [[Dnieper River]] so he could not be pursued.<ref>A. N. Nasonov, ed., ''Novgorodskaia pervaia letopis: starshego i mladshego'' izvodov (Moscow and Leningrad: AN SSSR, 1950), 63, 267; John Fennell, ''The Crisis of Medieval Russia 1200-1304'' (London and New York: Longman,1983), 66-68.</ref>\n\nMstislav reigned in Halych until 1227, when [[boyar]] intrigues constrained him to leave the city to his son-in-law, [[Andrew of Hungary, Prince of Halych|Andrew of Hungary]]. Thereupon he retired to [[Torchesk]], where he died in 1228.{{Citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\n==Family==\nHe married to a daughter of [[Koten|Kotian]] khan of Kypchak and had issue:\n* Rostislava, wife of [[Yaroslav II of Vladimir]].\n* Anna, wife of [[Daniel of Galicia]].\n\n==Succession==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|Rurikovich||?||1228||name=Mstislav Mstislavich}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sviatoslav III of Vladimir|Sviatoslav Vsevolodovich]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prince of Novgorod]]|years=1210\u20131215}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Yaroslav II of Vladimir|Yaroslav Vsevolodovich]]}}\n{{s-vac|unknown}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of rulers of Galicia and Volhynia|Prince of Halych]]|years=1219\u20131227}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew of Hungary, Prince of Halych|Andrew of Hungary]]}}\n{{s-vac|unknown}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prince of Torchesk]]|years=1227\u20131228}}\n{{s-vac|unknown}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mstislavich, Mstislav}}\n[[Category:12th-century births]]\n[[Category:1228 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rurik dynasty]]\n[[Category:Rostislavichi family (Smolensk)]]\n[[Category:Princes of Novgorod]]\n[[Category:Princes of Halych]]\n[[Category:Princes of Torchesk]]\n[[Category:12th-century princes in Kievan Rus']]\n[[Category:13th-century princes in Kievan Rus']]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox monarchs]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|Mstislav the Daring of Chernigov|Mstislav of Chernigov}}\n[[File:\u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0430) \u0438 \u0414\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0439.jpg|thumb|Detail from the [[Millennium of Russia]] Monument: Mstislav Mstislavich, left, and Daniel of Galicia, his son-in-law]]\n'''Mstislav Mstislavich the Daring''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432 II \u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0423\u0434\u0430\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439}}, {{lang-uk|\u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430&#769;\u0432 \u041c\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430&#769;\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0423\u0434\u0430&#769;\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0439<ref>The original nickname was The Lucky (or The Fortunate), \"Udatny\", later transformed to \"Udaloy\", i.e. The Bold.</ref>}}) was one of the most popular and active princes of [[Kievan Rus']] in the decades preceding the [[Mongol invasion of Russia|Mongol invasion of Rus']].{{Attribution needed|date=September 2013}} He was the maternal grandfather of Prince [[Alexander Nevsky]], [[Prince of Novgorod]], [[Grand Prince of Kiev]] and [[Grand Prince of Vladimir]]. He also was the maternal grandfather of prince [[Lev Danylovich|Leo of Galicia]], who became [[Grand Prince of Kiev]].\n\nHe was the son of [[Mstislav Rostislavich|Mstislav the Brave]] of [[Smolensk]] by a princess of [[Ryazan]]. In 1193 and 1203, his bravery in the [[Kipchaks|Kypchak]] wars brought him fame all over Kievan Rus'. At that time, he married Maria, a daughter of Kypchak [[Khan (title)|Khan]] [[Koten|Kotian]]. In 1209 he was mentioned as a ruler of [[Principality of Toropets|Toropets]]. A year later, he came and took the [[Novgorod]]ian throne, seizing [[Sviatoslav Vsevolodovich of Vladimir|Sviatoslav Vsevolodovich]]'s men (Sviatoslav himself was detained in the archbishop's compound in Novgorod).<ref>Michael C. Paul, \"Was the Prince of Novgorod a 'Third-rate Bureaucrat' after 1136?\" ''Jahrb\u00fccher f\u00fcr Geschichte Osteuropas'' 56, No. 1 (2008): 91.</ref>\n\nOn his way to Novgorod, Mstislav delivered the key town of [[Torzhok]] from a siege laid to it by [[Vsevolod the Big Nest|Vsevolod&nbsp;III]] of [[Vladimir, Russia|Vladimir]]. He led two successful Novgorodian campaigns against the [[Chud]]es in 1212 and 1214. In 1215, he expelled [[Vsevolod IV of Kiev|Vsevolod&nbsp;IV]] from [[Kiev]] and elevated his uncle [[Mstislav III of Kiev|Mstislav Romanovich]] to the throne.<ref>Paul, \"Third-rate Bureaucrat\" 91-92.</ref>\n\nIn 1216, Mstislav mustered a large coalition of princes of Rus' which defeated [[Vladimir-Suzdal]] on the [[Battle of Lipitsa|Lipitsa River]]. After that he installed his ally [[Konstantin of Rostov]] as [[Grand Prince of Vladimir]] and married his own daughter to [[Yaroslav II of Russia|Yaroslav of Vladimir]], who had fortified himself in Torzhok. In the meantime, his other enemies had him deposed in Novgorod, and Mstislav had to abandon Northern Rus for [[Halych]]. In 1219, he concluded peace with his chief rival, [[Danylo of Halych]], who thereupon married Mstislav's daughter Anna.{{Citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nIn 1223, Mstislav joined a coalition of perhaps 18 princes, which, along with [[Cuman]] (Polovtsian) allies, pursued the [[Mongols]] from the Dnieper River for nine days and joined battle with them at [[Battle of the Kalka River|Kalka River]].  While three princes were captured and later killed at the battle site, and six more were killed in headlong pursuit back to the Dnieper River, Mstislav is the only prince specifically named among the nine or so who escaped.  He managed to escape by cutting loose the boats on the [[Dnieper River]] so he could not be pursued.<ref>A. N. Nasonov, ed., ''Novgorodskaia pervaia letopis: starshego i mladshego'' izvodov (Moscow and Leningrad: AN SSSR, 1950), 63, 267; John Fennell, ''The Crisis of Medieval Russia 1200-1304'' (London and New York: Longman,1983), 66-68.</ref>\n\nMstislav reigned in Halych until 1227, when [[boyar]] intrigues constrained him to leave the city to his son-in-law, [[Andrew of Hungary, Prince of Halych|Andrew of Hungary]]. Thereupon he retired to [[Torchesk]], where he died in 1228.{{Citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\n==Family==\nHe married to a daughter of [[Koten|Kotian]] khan of Kypchak and had issue:\n* Rostislava, wife of [[Yaroslav II of Vladimir]].\n* Anna, wife of [[Daniel of Galicia]].\n\n==Succession==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|Rurikovich||?||1228||name=Mstislav Mstislavich}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sviatoslav III of Vladimir|Sviatoslav Vsevolodovich]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prince of Novgorod]]|years=1210\u20131215}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Yaroslav II of Vladimir|Yaroslav Vsevolodovich]]}}\n{{s-vac|unknown}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of rulers of Galicia and Volhynia|Prince of Halych]]|years=1219\u20131227}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew of Hungary, Prince of Halych|Andrew of Hungary]]}}\n{{s-vac|unknown}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prince of Torchesk]]|years=1227\u20131228}}\n{{s-vac|unknown}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mstislavich, Mstislav}}\n[[Category:12th-century births]]\n[[Category:1228 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rurik dynasty]]\n[[Category:Rostislavichi family (Smolensk)]]\n[[Category:Princes of Novgorod]]\n[[Category:Princes of Halych]]\n[[Category:Princes of Torchesk]]\n[[Category:12th-century princes in Kievan Rus']]\n[[Category:13th-century princes in Kievan Rus']]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox monarchs]]\n", "name_user": "MilHistExp", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mstislav_Mstislavich"}
